      "text": "Understanding the 2025 Transitional Interconnection Process (FERC Order No. 2023)\n\nLoading\n\n## Nov 19, 2025Knowledge\n\n### Information\n\nTitle\n\nUnderstanding the 2025 Transitional Interconnection Process (FERC Order No. 2023)\n\nContent\n\nThe Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued Order No. 2023 and (Improvements to Generator Interconnection Procedures and Agreements Key Project) to reform the current interconnection process used in the United States. These changes affect projects with an interconnection request (IR).\n\nFor ISO New England, this has involved a shift from a \"first-come, first-served\" serial study process to a cluster study approach, where multiple interconnection requests are evaluated simultaneously. The ISO submitted a compliance proposal in May 2024. FERC largely accepted the filing in April 2025 with an effective date of August 12, 2024.\n\nKey changes include:\n\n- a 270-day cluster study timeline (longer than FERC's pro forma 150 days, justified by regional complexities)\n- increased financial readiness deposits to deter speculative projects\n- the establishment of transitional study processes for projects already in the queue\n\n## Video\n\nWatch the video below (~9 minutes) to get a high-level overview of Order No. 2023. Then scroll down for recommended next steps and additional resources.\n\n## Next Steps\n\nDetermine your interest in and eligibility for the transitional processes associated with Order 2023: the Transitional Cluster Study and the Transitional CNR Group Study. Familiarize yourself with the eligibility rules and timeline including deadlines and requirements to adequately prepare.\n\n## Key Dates\n\nDownload an infographic of Order No. 2023 key dates (.pdf).\n\n- May 14, 2024: ISO New England’s Compliance Filing date\n- June 13, 2024: Eligibility Date (IRs will not be accepted again until October 5, 2026)\n- August 12, 2024: Effective Date\n- August 11, 2025: Transitional Cluster Study (TCS) Agreements sent to Interconnection Customers Participating in TCS\n- September 4, 2025: CNRC Transition Point\n- October 10, 2025: Transitional Cluster Study Agreements signed, data package, and financial deposits due\n- October 11, 2025: Transitional Cluster Study (TCS) starts\n- June 7, 2026: ISO provides interim TCS Report\n- August 6, 2026: ISO provides final TCS Report\n- August 21, 2026: Interconnection Agreement (IA) Negotiations begin for 60 calendar days\n- October 5, 2026: Initial Cluster Request Window opens for 45 calendar days\n- October 20, 2026: IA negotiation ends and IAs must be executed/effective\n\nYou should review the relevant changes to the Tariff. Visit the Order No. 2023 Key Project page on the ISO website for an aggregated list of all committee materials, FERC filings and orders, and links to learning aids to help guide stakeholders through the new processes. The final versions for each document will be posted on the Effective Date once the FERC has approved the filing. Submit any questions that you may have to irtt@iso-ne.com.\n\n## Resources\n\n- View the August 28, 2025 Transitional Cluster Study (Order No. 2023) Forum presentation or recording\n- Visit the Order No. 2023 Key Project page on the ISO website\n- Read the Interconnection Process Guide on the ISO website\n- View the 2025 Interim Reconfiguration Auction Qualification Process timeline\n- View the ISO Public Generator Interconnection Queue\n- View ISO-NE Planning Procedure 5-6\n\nLast Modified Date\n\n11/20/2025 2:15 PM\n\nURL Name\n\nUnderstanding-the-2024-Transitional-Interconnection-Process-FERC-Order-Nos-2023-and-2023-A\n\nInterconnection Tariff, Rules, Procedures & Manuals\n\nDrop Files\n\nUpload FilesOr drop files\n\n## Trending Articles\n\n- Where does a participant submit or request a claimed capability audit?\n- How to pick-up a digital certificate\n- How to import (install) a digital certificate to use in Chrome or Edge\n- How to export (backup) a digital certificate\n- CROW Sandbox for New Will Hold CSO Capacity Supply Obligation Designation\n\nLoading\n\nUnderstanding the 2025 Transitional Interconnection Process (FERC Order No. 2023)",
